<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-11T16:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-11T16:36:00-05:00" n="547" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d547">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 033.1211/25</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Fletcher</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-11T15:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 11, 1918, 3 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1168. In an interview with President Carranza this morning I asked him
                            his impression of the President’s speech to the Mexican journalists. He
                            answered with a smile that it was very good and that he hoped it would
                            be corroborated by subsequent events and added that he had nothing more
                            to say. I read to him the last draft of the President’s Pan American
                            treaty plan<note n="1" xml:id="d547fn1">
                                <ref target="frus1916#pg_3">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1916, p.
                                3</ref>.</note> referred to in the speech, and explained the causes
                            which prevented its realization at the time proposed, and told him that
                            the President hoped to be able to secure its adoption later. He said he
                            had read something of it and seemed favorably disposed toward it.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Fletcher</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>